{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1209"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.04,0.06,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1209"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34805"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42247"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department by her daughter in a confused state. Her daughter states that her mother seems to have been rather lethargic over the last couple of days and had fallen over on a couple of occasions. When the daughter went into her bedroom this morning, her mother was disorientated and mumbling. She was unaware of where she was, so the daughter decided to bring her straight to hospital. She has a medical history of depression. Her medical history includes sertraline, which has only been commenced recently. The patient drinks about four to five standard drinks a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, apart from her disorientation in time and space, the patient does not have any abnormal signs on physical examination. Her pulse rate is 90/min and blood pressure 140/80mmHg. Her laboratory results are shown:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 112 mmol/L (135 - 145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.5 mmol/L (3.5 - 5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 90 mmol/L (95 - 110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality 900 mOsm/kg (500-850)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sodium 31 mmol/L (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Syndrome of inappropriate anti-diuretic hormone secretion (SIADH)","Addison\u0027s disease","Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy","Sertraline overdose","Alcohol withdrawal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has syndrome of \u003Cstrong\u003Einappropriate anti-diuretic hormone secretion (SIADH)\u003C/strong\u003E secondary to recent commencement of sertraline; given the low serum sodium, confusion, altered mental state, high urine osmolality and high urine sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn SIADH, anti-diuretic hormone is released in excess. This leads to increased AQP-2 in the apical membrane of the distal convoluted tubule and collecting duct of the nephron in the kidney, and increased resorption of water. This leads to high urine sodium and osmolality, and dilution of serum electrolytes (particularly sodium) with the reabsorbed water. This leads to hyponatraemia, which is the cause of this patient\u0027s confusion and altered mental state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause increased urine sodium and decreased serum sodium, it presents as an \u0022Addisonian crisis\u0022 which results in severe dehydration, vomiting, and muscle pain. This patient has a normal blood pressure, and no history of Addison\u0027s disease, thus, it is an unlikely cause of her presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E presents with confusion, ophthalmoplegia, and ataxia usually on a background of significant alcohol usage. It would not result in significant hyponatraemia or changes in urine sodium and osmolality, thus, is unlikely to be the cause of this patient\u0027s confusion and altered mental status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline overdose\u003C/strong\u003E can cause symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, dizziness, and confusion, but it is less likely to cause the specific electrolyte abnormalities seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with tremors, agitation, and hallucinations, and does not usually cause significant hyponatraemia or the specific changes in urine sodium and osmolality seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SSRIs can cause syndrome of inappropriate anti-diuretic hormone secretion."],"references":["Jacob S, Spinler SA. Hyponatremia associated with selective serotonin-reuptake inhibitors in older adults. Ann Pharmacother. 2006;40(9):1618-22. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16896026/","Sahay M, Sahay R. Hyponatremia: A practical approach. Indian J Endocrinol Metab. 2014;18(6):760-71. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4192979/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34805"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34805"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-31T12:51:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-31T12:51:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1209"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}